04593nam a22005775i 9780774818896DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20112011xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748188967 a10.59962/97807748188962doi  a(DE-B1597)661247  a(OCoLC)768304219  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aKE7709bW64 2011eb 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a342.7108/721 aWoo, Grace Li Xiu, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGhost Dancing with Colonialism :bDecolonization and Indigenous Rights at the Supreme Court of Canada /cGrace Li Xiu Woo. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b6 b&w photos, 3 charts, 6 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw and Society00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tParadigms and the British Empire -- tAnomalies -- tConceptual Structures -- tColonial and Postcolonial Legality -- tCase Study: Indigenous Rights and Decolonization at the Supreme Court of Canada -- tMethodology -- tInternal Architecture of the Court’s Reasoning -- tTrends and Dance Tunes -- tCan the Court Become Postcolonial? -- tAppendices -- tChronological List of Cases Studied -- tJudicial Careers -- tJudicial Reasoning Profiles -- tAssessment of Reasoning -- tUse of the Canadian Judicial Institution -- tNotes* -- tSelected Bibliography -- tGeneral Index -- tIndex of Cases -- tIndex of Legislation, Treaties, and Accords -- tLaw and Society0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSome assume that Canada earned a place among postcolonial states in 1982 when it took charge of its Constitution. Yet despite the formal recognition accorded to Aboriginal and treaty rights, Indigenous peoples continue to argue they are still being colonized. Grace Woo assesses this allegation using a binary model that distinguishes colonial from postcolonial legality. She argues that two legal paradigms governed the expansion of the British Empire, one based on popular consent, the other on conquest and the power to command. Despite the best intentions of lawyers and judges, the beliefs and practices of the colonial age continue to haunt Supreme Court of Canada rulings concerning Indigenous rights. The binary analysis applied in Ghost Dancing with Colonialism casts explanatory light on ongoing tensions between Canada and Indigenous peoples, suggesting new ways to bridge the cultural divide and arrive at a truly postcolonial justice system. Additional appendices and references for Ghost Dancing with Colonialism: Decolonization and Indigenous Rights at the Supreme Court of Canada can be found at https://circle.ubc.ca/handle/2429/34959.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanada. -- Constitution Act, 1982. 0aIndigenous peoples -- Canada -- Government relations. 0aIndigenous peoples -- Legal status, laws, etc. -- Canada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077481889640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774818896423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774818896/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c20